<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-092-650  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 092 650.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Systems News  Feb 27 1989 n406 p3(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>U.S. shuns technology role. (Bush Administration policy)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Peterson, Stacey.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Dept of Commerce's continued hands-off policy towarddeveloping commercial technologies such as high-definitiontelevision or superconductivity is an early indication of the BushAdministration's approach to technology policy.andP;  Ernest Ambler,acting undersecretary for technology in the Commerce Dept, said ina speech at the 1989 IEEE US technology policy conference that thefederal government 'should not' and 'cannot' exercise leadership.andO;A Sematech-type industry-government partnership is ruled out.andO;Current efforts out of the Technology Administration and officesof technology and commercial affairs involve such tasks aseliminating barriers to rapid commercialization of science andtechnology, encouraging supportive government policies andinitiating coordinative efforts such as industry consortia.andP;  Thekey administrative post of science advisor to the President isvacant.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. Department of Commerce. Technology AdministrationPolicyGovernment AgencyResearch and DevelopmentHigh TechnologyGovernment FundingNational Government.andO;Person:    Bush, George (commercial policy).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>